  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of my neighbors. Growing up in a neighborhood where many kids didn't have access to advanced science classes, I remember how the idea that 'boys don't do math' made some of them avoid even trying. My dad, who only went to primary school, never pushed me into STEM, but I did it anyway because I knew it was important for my future. Now, as a delivery driver who helps people get things they need, I've seen how stereotypes can affect people's confidence. When someone tells a kid they're 'not cut out for engineering,' that's a real barrier. We need to address this by creating environments where everyone feels safe to learn without fear of judgment. In my community, it's not about fancy programs or expensive tech—it's about simple things like having mentors who understand the struggles of people from similar backgrounds. I've noticed that when teachers or coaches talk to students in a way that shows they belong, the kids start believing in themselves more. So yes, we should address stereotype threat in STEM. It's not just about fixing the system—it's about building trust and showing that everyone has the potential to succeed. That's what really matters.",
